[Event "Baker Bridge - Finessing"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "W:KT543.6.832.K974 A.KJ98742.QJ.AJT QJ97.T53.AKT6.Q6 862.AQ.9754.8532"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
pass 1H pass 1NT pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 1, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "7a4b5f8896af3d27c29406312f8c39fbbfa9c3d564f2374398e5f9432186db12"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/finessing"]
[Student "S"]
{North is to play 4\H. East leads the \DA. The defenders take two \D tricks, then switch to a trump.

Losers:   \S=0  \H=0  \D=2  \C=2  Total = 4

The status is pretty clear, you've already lost the 2 \Ds so you have to keep your \C losers to just one. You have a good chance of pulling that off by playing for the \CK and \CQ to lie in different hands and taking two finesses.

But you will only be in dummy once more so you <b>MUST</b> make the first finesse right now. Play a small \C from dummy and play the \CT. East wins with the \CQ and plays another trump.

  In dummy for the last time you must now take your second \C finesse. You play a small \C to your \CJ. When the \CJ wins you pull any leftover trumps and your hand is good.

This Deal is an excellent example of how and when to use the Double-Finesse, which gives you a 75% chance of success.

It was probably a better example of watching your entries. If you had pulled another trump before taking that first \C finesse you would not have been able to take the second one.}
[Play "W"]DA

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
