[Deal "N:JT92.T98.4.AJ953 AQ5.AK75.KQ9863. K86.Q432.5.KQT42 743.J6.AJT72.876"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6D"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "N"]
pass 1D pass 2D pass 3H pass 5D pass 6D pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "d3dd1a504cc04a7e2376174b93348d9430dac52b8f93c0fe53ec83cef791f3eb"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/finessing"]
[Student "S"]
{East is to play 6\D. South leads the \CK.

Losers:   \S=2  \H=2  \D=0  \C=0  Total = 4

You don't really have 2 \H losers since both of them can be ruffed in dummy. The 2 \S losers are real, though, and must be dealt with. If North holds the \SK then a simple finesse will win the contract for you. A 50% chance. But there is more to this Deal than a simple finesse, look at it carefully.

In addition to the trumps, dummy has another useful card, the \HJ. You can give yourself a second chance by playing South to hold the \HQ.

Ruff the opening \C lead, pull trumps with the \DK, (they split 1-1), and play a low \H toward the \HJ. South fidgets, then puts on the \HQ and plays another \C which you ruff.

You are in control now. You play a \H to dummy's \HJ, then a \S back to your \SA. Discard dummy's 2 \S losers on the \H A K and claim your slam.

Suppose that it was North who held the \HQ. Your \HJ would have been taken and you wouldn't get the two \S discards.

Then you would have to rely on the \S finesse after all. You'd be no worse off because you could still discard one of dummy's \Ss on a big \H.

This method of play gave you two chances instead of just one.}
[Play "W"]CK

